result.execSummary:
Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt: for the 6/10/19 Sentence After Revocation filed by Court Reporter Marjorie Kurtz

09:15 AM Defendant Tyler J Moll in court, in custody with attorney Alexander J. Kostal.  Roy Robert Korte appeared for the State of Wisconsin. Cases called: 14CF104, 14CF103, 14CF298, and 14CF319. The only case being revoked is 14CF104. All other cases had dismissed but read in charges, with a probation term that has been completed. In 14CF104 Sentencing argument by Special Prosecutor Roy Korte. Power point played by Atty Kostal. Sentencing argument by Atty Kostal. Defendant made a statement to the Court. Court sentenced the defendant to serve 10 years in prison, consecutive to Dane County Case 14CF308, 4 years initial confinement and 6 years extended supervision. All prior conditions of probation are remain for extended supervision. Defendant is not eligible for the Challenge Incarceration Program or The Substance Abuse Program. 328 days credit. Atty Korte requested the Power Point be put in the file and Sealed. Atty Kostal had no objection. Court granted the request.
Sentencing hearing on revocation on June 10, 2019 at 09:00 am.
